INDEX -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe development of the Thai-American alliance from 1947 to 1958 dramatically transformed both countries' involvement in Southeast Asia. Bounded by two important political events in Thailand, an army coup in 1947 and the military's assumption of complete control of government in 1958, the period witnessed both the entrenchment of authoritarian military government in Thailand and a revolution in U.S.-Thai relations. During these years the modern Thai political system emerged, and the United States established its interest and influence in mainland Southeast Asian affairs. The developments of the period made possible American's later, more extensive, involvement in Indochina. A Special Relationship provides the most comprehensive analysis of this critical founding period of the Thai-American alliance. It reveals surprising new information on joint covert operations in Indochina, American support for suppression of government opponents, and CIA involvement in Thai domestic politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486441540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824864415423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824864415/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  